(2, 3, '16.352780, 120.343600', '<p>ADPLS is located on the eastern side of Lingayen Gulf, along the coastal areas of the municipalities of Agoo, Sto. Tomas, and Rosario in southern La Union, Philippines.&nbsp;</p><p>ADPLS has a total area of 10,774.68 ha, with a marine area cover of 10,564.68 ha (98%), terrestrial area of 210 ha (2%), and with approximately 26.4 km combined coastline of the three municipalities. ADPLS has a Strict Protection Zone/Habitat Conservation/Restoration Zone of 2,253.34 ha (20.91%) and a Multiple Use Zone of 8,521.34 ha (79.09%).</p><div><br></div>', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/26_brunei_tasek_merimbun_nycticebus_coucang1.webp', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/tasek-merimbun-heritage-park/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '16.35278', '120.3436', '2', 'Agoo-Damortis Protected Landscape and Seascape (ADPLS)', '0', '1', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"5558\";s:3:\"url\";s:110:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/26_brunei_tasek_merimbun_nycticebus_coucang1.webp\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:110:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/26_brunei_tasek_merimbun_nycticebus_coucang1.webp\";}}}}', 0x000000000101000000d1ae42ca4f5a3040f5b9da8afd155e40, 1),
(3, 3, '-0.435123, 121.900017', '<div>The Kepulauan Togean Islands are an archipelago located in the transition zone of the Wallace and Weber lines and are a group of small islands that cross in the middle of the Gulf of Tomini.&nbsp;</div><div>KTNP area is located administratively in Tojo Una-Una regency, Central Sulawesi province, extending about 102.7 km from west to east line. It has become part of the Tojo Una-Una Togean Biosphere Reserve based on the 31st International Co-ordinating Council of the Man and Biosphere Program on 19 June 2019 in Paris, France.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div>', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/RGalsim_IMG_0144-scaled.webp', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/preah-monivong-bokor-national-park/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '-0.435123', '121.900017', '2', 'Kepulauan Togean National Park (KTNP)', '0', '2', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"5581\";s:3:\"url\";s:89:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/RGalsim_IMG_0144-scaled.webp\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:89:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/RGalsim_IMG_0144-scaled.webp\";}}}}', 0x000000000101000000b131af230ed9dbbf0536e7e099795e40, 0),
(4, 3, '-5.728100, 124.077797', '<div>Wakatobi National Park is a marine national park in Southeast Sulawesi, Indonesia based on the Minister of Environment and Forestry Decree number: SK149/IV-KK/2007.<br>The name of Wakatobi is a portmanteau of the four main Tukangbesi Islands: Wangi-Wangi, Kaledupa, Tomia, and Binongko. In 2012, Wakatobi National Park was recognised by UNESCO as part of the “World Network of Biosphere Reserves”. It consists of four larger islands: Wangi-Wangi, Kaledupa, Tomia, and Binongko, as well as many small islands such as Tokobao, North Lintea, South Lintea, Kampenaune, Hoga and Tolandono. The highest elevation is 274 metres (899 ft) on Wangi-Wangi, followed by Lagole Hill (271m) on Tomia, Terpadu Hill (222 m) on Binongko, and Mount Sampuagiwolo (203 m) on Kadelupa.&nbsp;<br></div><div><br></div>', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Bantimurung_PQReblora_IMG_20220811_153840-scaled.jpg', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/bantimurung-bulusaraung-national-park/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '-5.7281', '124.077797', '2', 'Wakatobi National Park (WNP)', '0', '3', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"6507\";s:3:\"url\";s:113:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Bantimurung_PQReblora_IMG_20220811_153840-scaled.jpg\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:113:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Bantimurung_PQReblora_IMG_20220811_153840-scaled.jpg\";}}}}', 0x000000000101000000d3dee00b93e916c086ae44a0fa045f40, 0),
(5, 3, '6.578, 99.477', 'Established as a national park in 1982, Similan Islands are an archipelago of 11 islands in the Andaman Sea, 70 km off the coast in Phang Nga province. The park covers an area of 140 km², of which 26 km² is an island. The national park consists of numerous islands: Bon, Kaow or Ba Ngu, Pad or Similan (the largest island of Mu Ko Similan), Hin Pu Sar, Jet or Pa Yu, Ha-Hok, Si or Miang, Sam or Pa Yan, Song or Pa Yang, Nung or Hu Yong and Ta Chai Islands. It also includes steep granite mountains, beaches, and rock formation of many shapes. The shoreline of each island is of inconsistent curves since they are situated in the outer part of the sea and are worn away directly by waves.&nbsp;', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/1710518698468-scaled.jpg', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/nam-ha-national-protected-area/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '6.578', '99.477', '2', 'Muko Similan National Park (MSiNP)', '0', '9', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"6549\";s:3:\"url\";s:85:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/1710518698468-scaled.jpg\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:85:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/1710518698468-scaled.jpg\";}}}}', 0x0000000001010000001d5a643bdf4f1a404a0c022b87de5840, 0),
(6, 3, '9.419, 97.868', 'Surin Islands are an archipelago of five islands within MSrNP in Phang Nga province. The islands are 55 km off the coast, 100 km north from Similan Islands in the Andaman Sea, and just 18 km from the marine border of Burma. The national park covers an area of 135 km² of which 76% is sea.&nbsp;', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/DSC_6718s-scaled.jpg', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/endau-rompin-johor-national-park/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '9.419', '97.868', '2', 'Muko Surin National Park (MSrNP)', '0', '4', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"6567\";s:3:\"url\";s:81:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/DSC_6718s-scaled.jpg\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:81:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/DSC_6718s-scaled.jpg\";}}}}', 0x0000000001010000004a0c022b87d62240643bdf4f8d775840, 0),
(7, 3, '9.834, 98.542', 'The Ranong Biosphere Reserve was declared as a biosphere reserve in 1997, and is situated 650 km south of Bangkok along the Andaman coast of the isthmus of Thailand. RBR incorporates a range of diversified natural and disturbed habitats including mangrove forests, tropical evergreen forests, open sea, seagrass beds, and urban and agricultural land. However, mangroves are the most representative ecosystem within this biosphere reserve.', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Kyaw-Naing-Lin-Hearts-scaled.jpg', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/alaungdaw-kathapa-national-park/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '9.834', '98.542', '0', 'Ranong Biosphere Reserve (RBR)', '0', '5', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"6612\";s:3:\"url\";s:93:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Kyaw-Naing-Lin-Hearts-scaled.jpg\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:93:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Kyaw-Naing-Lin-Hearts-scaled.jpg\";}}}}', 0x0000000001010000005eba490c02ab2340a69bc420b0a25840, 0),
(8, 3, '6.578, 99.477', 'TNP was established as a marine national park in 1974 and is located at the southernmost part of Thailand off the coast at Satun province in the Andaman Sea. The southern side of the national park is 4.8 km from the Thai-Malaysia border. The park consists of 51 islands within two groups: Tarutao Group to the east and Adang-Rawi Group to the west. There are three archipelagos in the park: Tarutao Archipelago, Klang Archipelago, and Adang Archipelago.&nbsp;<br>', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/panlabuhan-lake3-scaled.jpg', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/agusan-marsh-wildlife-sanctuary/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '6.578', '99.477', '2', 'Tarutao National Park (TNP)', '0', '6', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"6679\";s:3:\"url\";s:88:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/panlabuhan-lake3-scaled.jpg\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:88:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/panlabuhan-lake3-scaled.jpg\";}}}}', 0x0000000001010000001d5a643bdf4f1a404a0c022b87de5840, 0),
(9, 3, '12.887685, 123.425794', '<div></div><div>TBPPS is one of the marine biodiversity corridors of the Philippines and the largest fishing ground in the Bicol region. It was established as a nationally protected area under RA No. 11038 known as “Expanded National Integrated Protected Areas System (ENIPAS) Act of 2018.&nbsp;<br></div><div><br></div><div>The area serves as habitat to ecologically rich and biologically important species within its coverage of 413,745 ha in the provinces of Masbate, Sorsogon, Albay, and Camarines Sur in the Bicol region.<br></div><div><br></div>', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/92-singapore_bukit-timah_flora.jpg', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/bukit-timah-nature-reserve/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '12.887685', '123.425794', '2', 'Ticao-Burias Pass Protected Seascape (TBPPS)', '0', '7', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"6800\";s:3:\"url\";s:95:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/92-singapore_bukit-timah_flora.jpg\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:95:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/92-singapore_bukit-timah_flora.jpg\";}}}}', 0x000000000101000000ad4cf8a57ec6294050357a3540db5e40, 0),
(10, 3, '8.953333, 119.867500', 'Tubbataha Reefs and surrounding waters in the central Sulu Sea, Palawan province was established as a protected area under Presidential Proclamation No. 306 on 11 August 1988 (then called Tubbataha Reef National Marine Park). It became officially known as the Tubbataha Reefs Natural Park on 16 April 2010 by RA No. 10067 under the NIPAS Act (RA No. 7586) and the Strategic Environmental Plan (SEP) for Palawan Act (RA No. 7611).', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/1710522405083-scaled.jpg', 'https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/asean-heritage-parks/ao-phang-nga-mu-ko-surin-mu-ko-similan-national-park/', '{\"hover_url\":\"\\/\\/www.aseanbiodiversity.org\\/wp-content\\/plugins\\/wp-google-maps\\/images\\/spotlight-poi3.png\",\"hover_retina\":false}', '8.953333', '119.8675', '2', 'Tubbataha Reefs Natural Park (TRNP)', '0', '8', 1, 0, 0, '', 0, 'a:1:{s:7:\"gallery\";O:20:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGallery\":1:{s:8:\"\0*\0items\";a:1:{i:0;O:24:\"WPGMZA\\MarkerGalleryItem\":3:{s:13:\"attachment_id\";s:4:\"6809\";s:3:\"url\";s:85:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/1710522405083-scaled.jpg\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:85:\"https://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/1710522405083-scaled.jpg\";}}}}', 0x000000000101000000286552431be82140ec51b81e85f75d40, 0),
